Alerts

  1. Risk=Medium, Confidence=High (7)

    1. https://www.mozilla.org (1)

      1. CSP: script-src unsafe-eval (1)
        1. GET https://www.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/140.0/whatsnew/?oldversion=139.0.4&utm_medium=firefox-desktop&utm_source=update&utm_campaign=140
          Alert tags
          • CWE-693
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          Content Security Policy (CSP) is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks. Including (but not limited to) Cross Site Scripting (XSS), and data injection attacks. These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.
          Other info

          script-src includes unsafe-eval.

        <p class="c-box-body">Use Quick Actions to type things like “print,” “screenshot,” or “clear history” right where you search.</p>
        <a class="c-box-cta mzp-c-button mzp-t-secondary" href="https://blog.mozilla.org/en/firefox/address-bar/?utm_source=www.mozilla.org&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=wnp140#quick-actions" data-cta-text="Learn more" data-cta-type="button"  target="_blank" rel="external noopener">Learn more</a>
      </section>

      <section class="c-box box-two">
        <img class="c-box-image" src="https://www.mozilla.org/media/img/l10n/en-US/firefox/wnp-140/bookmarks.a54e6159bc51.svg" alt="Bookmarks. Search bookmarks." width="298" height="167">
        <h2 class="c-box-title">Get straight to what you’ve saved</h2>
        <p class="c-box-body">Use @ Shortcuts like @bookmarks, @history, or @downloads to search specific parts of your browser instantly.</p>
        <a class="c-box-cta mzp-c-button mzp-t-secondary" href="https://blog.mozilla.org/en/firefox/address-bar/?utm_source=www.mozilla.org&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=wnp140#intuitive-search-keywords" data-cta-text="Learn more" data-cta-type="button" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">Learn more</a>
      </section>

      <section class="c-box box-three">
        <img class="c-box-image" src="https://www.mozilla.org/media/img/l10n/en-US/firefox/wnp-140/tab-search.7e054fc28776.svg" alt="Firefox suggest. Switch to tab." width="298" height="167">
        <h2 class="c-box-title">Find the tab you need easily</h2>
        <p class="c-box-body">With Tab Search, just start typing and Firefox shows matching open tabs so you can switch without the scroll.</p>
        <a class="c-box-cta mzp-c-button mzp-t-secondary" href="https://blog.mozilla.org/en/firefox/address-bar/?utm_source=www.mozilla.org&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=wnp140#smart-shortcuts" data-cta-text="Learn more" data-cta-type="button" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">Learn more</a>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>

    3. https://integrationqa.rvscommerce.com (5)

      1. CSP: Failure to Define Directive with No Fallback (1)
        1. GET https://integrationqa.rvscommerce.com/mahindraedi/assets/vendors/jquery-bar-rating/css-stars.css
          Alert tags
          • CWE-693
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Content Security Policy fails to define one of the directives that has no fallback. Missing/excluding them is the same as allowing anything.
          Other info

          The directive(s): form-action is/are among the directives that do not fallback to default-src.

      2. CSP: Wildcard Directive (1)
        1. GET https://integrationqa.rvscommerce.com/mahindraedi/assets/vendors/jquery-bar-rating/css-stars.css
          Alert tags
          • CWE-693
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          Content Security Policy (CSP) is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks. Including (but not limited to) Cross Site Scripting (XSS), and data injection attacks. These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.
          Other info

          The following directives either allow wildcard sources (or ancestors), are not defined, or are overly broadly defined:

          script-src, style-src, img-src, connect-src, frame-src, font-src, media-src, object-src, manifest-src, worker-src

    1. https://integrationqa.rvscommerce.com (1)

      1. Absence of Anti-CSRF Tokens (1)
        1. GET https://integrationqa.rvscommerce.com/mahindraedi/Dashboard.aspx
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A01
          • WSTG-v42-SESS-05
          • OWASP_2017_A05
          • CWE-352
          Alert description

          No Anti-CSRF tokens were found in a HTML submission form.

          A cross-site request forgery is an attack that involves forcing a victim to send an HTTP request to a target destination without their knowledge or intent in order to perform an action as the victim. The underlying cause is application functionality using predictable URL/form actions in a repeatable way. The nature of the attack is that CSRF exploits the trust that a web site has for a user. By contrast, cross-site scripting (XSS) exploits the trust that a user has for a web site. Like XSS, CSRF attacks are not necessarily cross-site, but they can be. Cross-site request forgery is also known as CSRF, XSRF, one-click attack, session riding, confused deputy, and sea surf.

          CSRF attacks are effective in a number of situations, including:

          * The victim has an active session on the target site.

          * The victim is authenticated via HTTP auth on the target site.

          * The victim is on the same local network as the target site.

          CSRF has primarily been used to perform an action against a target site using the victim's privileges, but recent techniques have been discovered to disclose information by gaining access to the response. The risk of information disclosure is dramatically increased when the target site is vulnerable to XSS, because XSS can be used as a platform for CSRF, allowing the attack to operate within the bounds of the same-origin policy.
          Other info

          No known Anti-CSRF token [anticsrf, CSRFToken, __RequestVerificationToken, csrfmiddlewaretoken, authenticity_token, OWASP_CSRFTOKEN, anoncsrf, csrf_token, _csrf, _csrfSecret, __csrf_magic, CSRF, _token, _csrf_token, _csrfToken] was found in the following HTML form: [Form 1: "__EVENTVALIDATION" "__VIEWSTATE" "__VIEWSTATEGENERATOR" "btnLogout" ].

          Evidence 
          <form method="post" action="./Dashboard.aspx" id="form1">
          Solution

          Phase: Architecture and Design

          Use a vetted library or framework that does not allow this weakness to occur or provides constructs that make this weakness easier to avoid.

          For example, use anti-CSRF packages such as the OWASP CSRFGuard.

          Phase: Implementation

          Ensure that your application is free of cross-site scripting issues, because most CSRF defenses can be bypassed using attacker-controlled script.

          Phase: Architecture and Design

          Generate a unique nonce for each form, place the nonce into the form, and verify the nonce upon receipt of the form. Be sure that the nonce is not predictable (CWE-330).

          Note that this can be bypassed using XSS.

          Identify especially dangerous operations. When the user performs a dangerous operation, send a separate confirmation request to ensure that the user intended to perform that operation.

          Note that this can be bypassed using XSS.

          Use the ESAPI Session Management control.

          This control includes a component for CSRF.

          Do not use the GET method for any request that triggers a state change.

          Phase: Implementation

          Check the HTTP Referer header to see if the request originated from an expected page. This could break legitimate functionality, because users or proxies may have disabled sending the Referer for privacy reasons.

  4. Risk=Low, Confidence=High (4)

    1. https://js.driftt.com (1)

      1. Strict-Transport-Security Multiple Header Entries (Non-compliant with Spec) (1)
        1. GET https://js.driftt.com/include/1750944600000/uc5xu7xrzxrr.js
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          • CWE-319
          Alert description

          HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) headers were found, a response with multiple HSTS header entries is not compliant with the specification (RFC 6797) and only the first HSTS header will be processed others will be ignored by user agents or the HSTS policy may be incorrectly applied.

          HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) is a web security policy mechanism whereby a web server declares that complying user agents (such as a web browser) are to interact with it using only secure HTTPS connections (i.e. HTTP layered over TLS/SSL).

          Alert tags
          • CWE-693
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          Content Security Policy (CSP) is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks. Including (but not limited to) Cross Site Scripting (XSS), and data injection attacks. These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.
          Other info

          Warnings:

          The report-uri directive has been deprecated in favor of the new report-to directive

          HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) is a web security policy mechanism whereby a web server declares that complying user agents (such as a web browser) are to interact with it using only secure HTTPS connections (i.e. HTTP layered over TLS/SSL). HSTS is an IETF standards track protocol and is specified in RFC 6797.

									Get programmatic access to our detection methods by signing up for a free or premium API plan. </p><a href="/Documentation" class="btn btn-lg btn-info text-white" title="Documentation">Documentation</a> &nbsp; <a href="/API" class="btn btn-lg btn-secondary" title="Get an API key">Get an API key</a></div><div class="px-5 hidden-sm"><span style="position:relative;display:inline-block;"><i class="ic et-global text-info m-3" style="font-size:10rem"></i></span></div></div></div><div class="h-30 bg-light border-top"><div class="d-flex justify-content-center" style="margin:auto"><div class="px-5 hidden-sm"><span style="position:relative;display:inline-block;"><i class="ic et-layers text-info m-3" style="font-size:10rem"></i></span></div><div class="col-md-7"><h2>Detection Network</h2><p class="lead">Enrich your company and website data even more.
				 					API accounts with WhatCMS give you access to endpoints for hosting provider and WordPress theme data.</p><p><a href="https://www.who-hosts-this.com" class="btn btn-lg btn-info text-white">Hosting Provider Detection</a></p>
									<p><a href="https://www.themedetect.com" class="btn btn-lg btn-info text-white">WordPress Theme Detection</a></sp></div></div></div><div class="h-30  border-top"><div class="d-flex justify-content-center" style="margin:auto"><div class="col-md-7"><h2>What is a CMS?</h2><p class="lead">A Content Management System, or CMS, is a piece of software designed to help users create and edit websites.
									CMS functionality varies widely and can include much more than the basic features for managing text and image content.
									Some of the most popular systems help users design, track users, handle searches, collect visitor comments, host forums and much much more.</p></div><div class="px-5 hidden-sm"><span style="position:relative;display:inline-block;"><i class="ic ph-question-thin text-info m-3" style="font-size:10rem"></i></span></div></div></div><div class="h-30 bg-light border-top"><div class="d-flex justify-content-center" style="margin:auto"><div class="px-5 hidden-sm"><span style="position:relative;display:inline-block;"><i class="ic et-magnifying-glass text-info m-3" style="font-size:10rem"></i></span></div><div class="col-md-7"><h2>How Our Detections Work</h2><p class="lead">We look at a variety of factors to determine which technologies a website is using.
									After fetching a webpage we begin looking for artifacts that were left behind by the underlying systems.
									In HTML, we look for things like &lt;meta name="generator"&gt; tags and common paths for images.
									We inspect for custom headers and common session names.
									In all, we check every page for thousands of possible artifacts before returning the results.

      4. X-Content-Type-Options Header Missing (1)
        1. GET https://integrationqa.rvscommerce.com/mahindraedi/Dashboard.aspx
          Alert tags
          • CWE-693
          • OWASP_2021_A05
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          Alert description

          The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
          Other info

          This issue still applies to error type pages (401, 403, 500, etc.) as those pages are often still affected by injection issues, in which case there is still concern for browsers sniffing pages away from their actual content type.

          At "High" threshold this scan rule will not alert on client or server error responses.

CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.

  <div class="wnp-content-main mzp-l-content mzp-t-content-max">
    <h1 class="wnp-main-title">Search smarter. Do more. All from your address bar.</h1>
    <div class="mzp-l-columns mzp-t-columns-three">
      <section class="c-box box-one">
        <img class="c-box-image" src="https://www.mozilla.org/media/img/l10n/en-US/firefox/wnp-140/quick-actions.5697b5b51e48.svg" alt="Screenshot. Take a screenshot." width="298" height="167">
        <h2 class="c-box-title">Handle everyday tasks in a flash</h2>
        <p class="c-box-body">Use Quick Actions to type things like “print,” “screenshot,” or “clear history” right where you search.</p>
        <a class="c-box-cta mzp-c-button mzp-t-secondary" href="https://blog.mozilla.org/en/firefox/address-bar/?utm_source=www.mozilla.org&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=wnp140#quick-actions" data-cta-text="Learn more" data-cta-type="button"  target="_blank" rel="external noopener">Learn more</a>
      </section>

      <section class="c-box box-two">
        <img class="c-box-image" src="https://www.mozilla.org/media/img/l10n/en-US/firefox/wnp-140/bookmarks.a54e6159bc51.svg" alt="Bookmarks. Search bookmarks." width="298" height="167">
        <h2 class="c-box-title">Get straight to what you’ve saved</h2>
        <p class="c-box-body">Use @ Shortcuts like @bookmarks, @history, or @downloads to search specific parts of your browser instantly.</p>
        <a class="c-box-cta mzp-c-button mzp-t-secondary" href="https://blog.mozilla.org/en/firefox/address-bar/?utm_source=www.mozilla.org&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=wnp140#intuitive-search-keywords" data-cta-text="Learn more" data-cta-type="button" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">Learn more</a>
      </section>

      <section class="c-box box-three">
        <img class="c-box-image" src="https://www.mozilla.org/media/img/l10n/en-US/firefox/wnp-140/tab-search.7e054fc28776.svg" alt="Firefox suggest. Switch to tab." width="298" height="167">
        <h2 class="c-box-title">Find the tab you need easily</h2>
        <p class="c-box-body">With Tab Search, just start typing and Firefox shows matching open tabs so you can switch without the scroll.</p>
        <a class="c-box-cta mzp-c-button mzp-t-secondary" href="https://blog.mozilla.org/en/firefox/address-bar/?utm_source=www.mozilla.org&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=wnp140#smart-shortcuts" data-cta-text="Learn more" data-cta-type="button" target="_blank" rel="external noopener">Learn more</a>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>

        function validateInput() {
            var tempSupplier_Name;
            var tempSupplier_Code;
            var tempSupplier_Address;
            tempSupplier_Name = document.getElementById("txtSupplier_Name").value;
            tempSupplier_Code = document.getElementById("txtSupplier_Code").value;
            tempSupplier_Address = document.getElementById("txtSupplier_Address").value;

            if (tempSupplier_Name.trim() == "")
            {
                alert("Supplier Name is missing");
                return false;
            }
            if (tempSupplier_Code.trim() == "")
            {
                alert("Supplier Code is missing");
                return false;
            }
            if (tempSupplier_Address.trim() == "")
            {
                alert("Supplier Address is missing");
                return false;
            }
        }

        function validateFileUploadInput() {
            var fileimage = document.getElementById("FileUpload1");

            if (fileimage.value == '') {
                alert("Please Select a file");
                return false;
            }

            if (fileimage.value != '') {
                var arrayF1 = ['xlsx'];
                var xyzF1 = document.getElementById("FileUpload1");
                var ExtensionF1 = xyzF1.value.substring(xyzF1.value.lastIndexOf('.') + 1).toLowerCase();
                if (arrayF1.indexOf(ExtensionF1) <= -1) {
                    alert("Please Upload only xlsx file");
                    return false;
                }
            }
        }

This configuration is typically found in corporate or educational environments, for instance.

      1. Loosely Scoped Cookie (1)
        1. POST https://ab.chatgpt.com/v1/rgstr?k=client-nb0qtYlZuy2tCMN5s5ncnuIBCJncjRViT0IzFm7GqST&st=javascript-client&sv=3.17.0&t=1750944017753&sid=ef302583-0c3b-43ac-8e82-3c1b784bca0d&ec=12&gz=1
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2021_A08
          • CWE-565
          • OWASP_2017_A06
          • WSTG-v42-SESS-02
          Alert description

          Cookies can be scoped by domain or path. This check is only concerned with domain scope.The domain scope applied to a cookie determines which domains can access it. For example, a cookie can be scoped strictly to a subdomain e.g. www.nottrusted.com, or loosely scoped to a parent domain e.g. nottrusted.com. In the latter case, any subdomain of nottrusted.com can access the cookie. Loosely scoped cookies are common in mega-applications like google.com and live.com. Cookies set from a subdomain like app.foo.bar are transmitted only to that domain by the browser. However, cookies scoped to a parent-level domain may be transmitted to the parent, or any subdomain of the parent.

      3. User Controllable HTML Element Attribute (Potential XSS) (1)
        1. GET https://integrationqa.rvscommerce.com/mahindraedi/Login.aspx?ReturnUrl=%2fmahindraedi
          Alert tags
          • OWASP_2017_A01
          • CWE-20
          • OWASP_2021_A03
          Alert description

          This check looks at user-supplied input in query string parameters and POST data to identify where certain HTML attribute values might be controlled. This provides hot-spot detection for XSS (cross-site scripting) that will require further review by a security analyst to determine exploitability.
